ive multimodal agents, 2026. URL https://qwen.ai/blog?id=qwen3.5 . Appendix A Additional \n\n## Experiments A.1 Effect of Audio-Centric Augmentation As shown in our main experiments, while omni-modal foundation models exhibit robust Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) capabilities, they frequently struggle with non-speech auditory events. To quantify this phenomenon and validate our solution, we conduct an ablation study analyzing the impact of our audio-centric augmentation during the Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) stage. We first train a baseline model exclusively on the 40K video-text p\nairs. As detailed in the top row of Table 7 , this model achieves a strong Speech Recall of 70.08%, confirming that the base model already possesses solid speech perception from its pre-training. However, it exhibits evident weaknesses in recognizing specific environmental sounds ( SFX : 26.35%) and musical properties ( Music : 35.98%). SFT Data Visual Audio Synergy Total Speech Music SFX Overall 40K 59.65 70.08 35.98 26.35 62.05 53.10 58.27 40K + 10K 59.80 70.15 39.50 29.80 64.20 54.26 59.42 Δ \n\\Delta +0.15 +0.07 +3.52 +3.45 +2.15 +1.16 +1.15 Table 7: \n\n## Ablation on audio-centric augmentation during the SFT stage. Evaluated on \n","numLines":200,"startLine":150,"totalLines":539}}}
